To tackle the issue, I would start with early exposure. Schools can host science nights where parents and teachers bring in female scientists or use interactive media to show that curiosity, not gender, matters. At the university level, scholarships earmarked for women and non-binary students help lower financial barriers. Mentorship programs should pair junior researchers with senior mentors who understand the unique challenges of underrepresented genders; this can be facilitated through professional societies. In the workplace, transparent promotion criteria and regular bias training can reduce unconscious favoritism. Funding agencies could require gender diversity statements in grant proposals, encouraging applicants to think about inclusive team structures.

